                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" id="asianamerican_sng_2" fkcefr="b2" hclass="sense" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">being an <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/asian-american_1" title="Asian American definition"><span class="ndv">Asian American</span></a>; connected with <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/asian-american_1#asian_american_topg_1" title="Asian Americans definition"><span class="ndv">Asian Americans</span></a></span></span><ul class="examples" hclass="examples" htag="ul"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">Asian-American families</span></li></ul> <span class="un" un="help">Many people dislike the use of very general terms such as <span class="eb">Asian</span>, <span class="eb">Asian American</span>, <span class="eb">Native American</span> or <span class="eb">BAME</span> because they put into a single category many groups of people, who may have different nationalities, languages, cultures, religions, backgrounds, experiences, etc. These terms can be useful in official contexts, for example when collecting statistics, but if you need to refer to an individual’s background it is often better to be specific and use terms such as <span class="ei">British Pakistani</span> or <span class="ei">Korean American</span>.</span><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/people-in-society?level=b2" title="Topic people-in-society"><span class="topic" href="l2:politics_and_society:people_in_society?cefr=b2"><span class="topic_name">People in society</span><span class="topic_cefr">b2</span></span></a></span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
